1. Availability: Seller makes electric energy, capacity and ancillary services available as a power marketer under this Rate Schedule for wholesale sales to any purchaser with whom Seller has contracted.
2. Applicability: This Rate Schedule is applicable to all sales of electric energy, capacity and ancillary services by Seller not otherwise subject to a particular Rate Schedule of Seller.
3. Rates: All sales shall be made at the rates established between Seller and the purchaser.
4. Other Terms and Conditions: All other terms and conditions shall be established by agreement between Seller and the purchaser.
5. Ancillary Services: Seller will make available to any purchaser with whom it has contracted, the ancillary services listed in this Paragraph.
a. PJM: Seller offers regulation and frequency response service, energy imbalance service, and operating reserve service (which includes spinning, 10-minute, and 30-minute reserves) for sale into the market administered by PJM Interconnection, L.L.C. ("PJM") and, where the PJM Open Access Transmission Tariff permits, the self-supply of these services to purchasers for a bilateral sale that is used to satisfy the ancillary services requirements of the PJM Office of Interconnection.
b. New York: Seller offers regulation and frequency response service, and operating reserve service (which include l0-minute non-synchronous, 30-minute operating reserves, l0-minute spinning reserves, and 10-minute non-spinning reserves) for sale to purchasers in the market administered by the New York Independent System Operator, Inc.
c. New England: Seller offers regulation and frequency response service (automatic generator control), operating reserve service (which includes 10-minute spinning reserve, 10-minute non-spinning reserve, and 30-minute operating reserve service) to purchasers within the markets administered by the ISO New England, Inc.
d. California: Seller offers regulation service, spinning reserve service, and non-spinning reserve service to the California Independent System Operator Corporation ("CAISO") and to others that are self-supplying ancillary services to the CAISO.
e. MISO: Seller offers regulation service and operating reserve service (which include 10-minute spinning reserve and 10-minute supplemental reserve) for sale to the Midcontinent Independent System Operator, Inc. ("MISO") and to others that are self-supplying ancillary services to MISO.
f. Southwest Power Pool: Seller offers regulation service and operating reserve service (which include 10-minute spinning reserve and 10-minute supplemental reserve) for sale to the Southwest Power Pool, Inc. ("SPP") and to others that are self-supplying ancillary services to SPP.
g. Third-Party Ancillary Services: Seller offers Regulation Service, Reactive Supply and Voltage Control Service, Energy and Generator Imbalance Service, Operating Reserve-Spinning, Operating Reserve-Supplemental, and Primary Frequency Response Service. Sales will not include the following: (1) sales to an RTO or an ISO, i.e., where that entity has no ability to self-supply ancillary services but instead depends on third parties; and (2) sales to a traditional, franchised public utility affiliated with the third-party supplier, or sales where the underlying transmission service is on the system of the public utility affiliated with the third-party supplier. Sales of Operating Reserve-Spinning and Operating Reserve-Supplemental will not include sales to a public utility that is purchasing ancillary services to satisfy its own open access transmission tariff requirements to offer ancillary services to its own customers, except where the Commission has granted authorization. Sales of Regulation Service and Reactive Supply and Voltage Control Service will not include sales to a public utility that is purchasing ancillary services to satisfy its own open access transmission tariff requirements to offer ancillary services to its own customers, except at rates not to exceed the buying public utility transmission provider's OATT rate for the same service or where the Commission has granted authorization.
6. Compliance with Commission Regulations: Seller shall comply with the provisions of 18 C.F.R. Part 35, Subpart H, as applicable, and with any conditions the Commission imposes in its orders concerning seller's market-based rate authority, including orders in which the Commission authorizes seller to engage in affiliate sales under this tariff or otherwise restricts or limits the seller's market-based rate authority. Failure to comply with the applicable provisions of 18 C.F.R. Part 35, Subpart H, and with any orders of the Commission concerning seller's market-based rate authority, will constitute a violation of this tariff.
7. Seller Category: As defined in 18 C.F.R. 35.36(a), Seller is a Category 1 seller in the Central, Southeast, Southwest Power Pool, Northeast, and Northwest regions and a Category 2 seller in the Southwest region, as defined in 18 C.F.R. 35.36(a).
8. Limitations and Exemptions Regarding Market-Based Rate Authority: Seller has received waiver of: Subparts B and C of Part 35, except for sections 35.12(a), 35.13(b), 35.15 and 35.16. Seller has also received waiver of: Part 41, Part 101, except that waiver of the provisions that apply to hydropower licenses has not been granted with respect to licensed hydropower projects and Part 141 with the exception of 18 C.F.R. 141.14 and 141.15. Seller has also received blanket approval under Part 34. (See Desert Quartzite, LLC, Docket No. ER24-____-000 (2024) (unpublished letter order)).
9. Effective Date: This Tariff is effective on the date specified by the Commission.

COTENANCY, COMMON ASSETS AND COMMON USE AGREEMENT This COTENANCY, COMMON ASSETS AND COMMON USE AGREEMENT (the Agreement) is made and entered into as of __March 29__, 2024 (the Effective Date) by and among DESERT QUARTZITE, LLC, a Delaware limited liability company (Desert Quartzite), CALYPSO SOLAR, LLC, a Delaware limited liability company (Calypso), and EDF Renewables Development, Inc., a Delaware corporation (EDF RD) (and its and their successor(s) in interest pursuant hereto). Each of Desert Quartzite, Calypso, and EDF RD and their permitted successors and assigns hereunder is sometimes referred to herein individually as an Owner or a Party and collectively referred to as the Owners or the Parties. RECITALS Desert Quartzite is developing a combined 300 MW solar photovoltaic (Solar PV) and 150 MW four-hour battery energy storage system project in Riverside County, CA (the Desert Quartzite Project). Calypso is developing a 400 MW Solar PV and 400 MW battery energy storage project in Riverside County, CA (the Calypso Project). Desert Quartzite has entered into two separate Large Generator Interconnection Agreements (Service Agreement # 221 and Service Agreement # 270) with Southern California Edison Company (SCE), dated 11/13/2018 and 07/09/2021 respectively, which provides for the interconnection and delivery of up to 300 MW (as measured at the Point of Interconnection) of energy from the Desert Quartzite Project to the Colorado River Substation (defined herein)(as further amended from time to time, the Desert Quartzite LGIA). A Material Modification Assessment is currently in review with SCE and the CAISO to combine the two LGIAs into one LGIA. Calypso has entered into a Large Generator Interconnection Agreement dated, April 25, 2023, by and among Calypso, SCE, and CAISO, which provides for the interconnection and delivery of up to 400 MW (as measured at the Point of Interconnection) of energy from the Calypso Project to the Colorado River Substation (as further amended from time to time, the Calypso LGIA). D. EDF RD and/or its permitted successors and assigns hereunder are (or will be) developing, and plan to construct, own and operate one or more Solar PV generating and/or battery storage projects and related facilities (the EDF RD Project(s)) which are contemplated to interconnect and deliver energy in an amount up to the Maximum Interconnection Capacity for the Common Facilities, to the Colorado River Substation. E. To avoid the costly duplication of facilities necessary to transmit the output of their respective Projects to the Colorado River Substation, the Owners are jointly developing and intend to share certain costs and ownership of certain gen-tie and substation facilities described on Exhibit A-3, (as the same may be modified and supplemented as permitted herein, collectively, Common Facilities). The Common Facilities will be co-owned and shared by the Owners as provided herein. F. Pursuant to (i) the Common Real Property Documents (defined herein) and (ii) those certain partial assignment and assumption or other agreements which may, in the future, be entered into by and between the Owners, each Owner holds or will hold its Common Facilities Ownership Percentage as tenants-in-common in the Common Premises, the Common Facilities, the Common Licenses and Permits and the Common Project Agreements and certain other shared developmental assets (collectively, the Common Assets), which shall be used by the Owners for the Common Facilities. In furtherance thereof, the Owners wish to set forth certain of their rights and responsibilities in respect of the development, construction and operation of the Common Assets necessary for the Projects. G. Each of the Owners expects to transmit electric energy generated from their respective Projects to the Colorado River Substation by sharing the use and ownership of the Common Assets. (a) In the event the Common Assets Manager becomes aware of an equipment failure or an unanticipated event that requires the use of the Common Facilities to be curtailed to protect the Common Facilities, any Project, or human life, or CAISO orders a curtailment of the Common Facilities, the Common Assets Manager shall immediately notify each Operating Owner or its designated scheduling agent. (c) To the extent any such curtailment or disconnection is directly caused by an act or omission of an Owner constituting negligence or willful misconduct or the breach by an Owner of this Agreement, then, notwithstanding subsection (b) above, (i) such Owners Project shall be the first Project to be curtailed or disconnected and, subject to the last sentence of this subsection (c), the last Project to be permitted to use the Common Assets following any such curtailment or disconnection, and (ii) such Owner shall be solely responsible for any and all lost revenues, costs and/or expenses (including the cash value of any lost federal tax credits, grossed-up based on the actual combined state and federal income tax rate applicable to such Owner) incurred by the other Owner(s) for any curtailment of some or all of the energy production attributable to such act, omission or breach. Article 3 OPERATION AND MAINTENANCE OF COMMON ASSETS 3.1 Operation and Maintenance of the Common Assets . Each Operating Owner shall pay its then-applicable Proportionate Share of all costs of operating and maintaining the Common Assets in accordance herewith during the time period such Owner is an Operating Owner hereunder, as such costs are established and approved by the Common Assets Manager, subject to each Operating Owners rights of approval and disapproval as set forth in Article 4. 3.2 Removal of Property . Each Owner shall have the express right, at any time and in its sole discretion, to remove and/or replace any part of its Project and all other property owned by such Owner, to the extent not jointly owned by the Owners. If removal or replacement of any of such property will materially affect in an adverse way the safety or operation of any of the Common Assets, the Owner contemplating the removal or replacement shall consult with and obtain the consent of the other Owner(s) and the Common Assets Manager before conducting the contemplated removal or replacement, such consent not to be unreasonably withheld, conditioned or delayed, and subject to compliance with reasonable requirements of the consenting Owner(s) and the Common Assets Manager in connection with the performance of such removal or replacement work to safeguard persons or property or minimize interference with operations. 3.3 Rights to Common Assets . Subject to Section 2.2(a), each Operating Owner shall have the right to hold and utilize its then-applicable undivided tenancy-in-common ownership percentage equal to such Owners Common Facilities Ownership Percentage set forth on Exhibit C (as the same may be updated and revised from time to time as provided herein) in each component of the Common Assets to interconnect and transmit electricity to and from its Project to the Interconnection Point up to such Owners Maximum Interconnection Capacity in accordance with the terms of this Agreement. 3.4 Common Expenses and Line Losses . (a) Each Operating Owner shall be obligated to pay all Common Expenses in proportion to such Operating Owners then-applicable Proportionate Share. The Common Assets Manager, as authorized agent for each Operating Owner, shall administer the collection and payment of the Common Expenses, either through a monthly invoice to an individual Operating Owner or a monthly invoice (as an aggregate expense) to all Operating Owners. Each Operating Owner shall pay each such invoice promptly upon, and in any event within thirty (30) days of, receipt of written notice thereof from the Common Assets Manager. The Operating Owners shall reimburse the Common Assets Manager for Common Expenses incurred by it in accordance with this Agreement. (b) As it becomes practicable and desirable, the Operating Owners from time to time may designate additional expenses as Common Expenses to be administered by the Common Assets Manager in accordance with this Section 3.4 to the extent such additional expenses are similar to the other Common Expenses. Notwithstanding the foregoing, no Owner shall be liable for any other Owners Project expenses. (c) Each Owner shall arrange for wholesale metering of its Project in accordance with its Interconnection Agreement and the Transmission Service Providers tariffs. The meter readings shall be adjusted to account for transformer and transmission line losses occurring between each Projects meter and the Interconnection Point in accordance with the Transmission Providers tariffs. Upon the request of any Owner, the other Owners shall provide the Transmission Service Provider and/or the other Owners (depending on who is calculating the transformer and transmission line losses) their meter data to the extent reasonably required for the purposes of calculating line losses on the Common Facilities. For purposes of clarity, the Parties agree that losses associated with any improvements which are not Common Facilities will be the responsibility of the applicable Owner of those improvements. (d) Notwithstanding anything to the contrary contained herein (except as otherwise provided in this Agreement), all costs, expenses and/or liabilities (other than Common Expenses) incurred by the Common Assets Manager or any Owner that are attributed to the permitting, licensing, construction, initial start-up, testing and/or interconnection of a Project shall be the sole cost of such Project. Any monies paid by the Common Assets Manager or any other Owner with respect to such items shall be promptly reimbursed by the applicable Owner. (e) Any agreement that is a Common Project Agreement or a Common Real Property Document or that otherwise results in Common Expenses, in each case, entered into with an Affiliate of any Owner shall contain fees charged based on fair market value in a comparable arms length transaction with an equally experienced Person not an Affiliate of an Owner. Article 4 COMMON ASSETS MANAGEMENT 4.1 Common Assets Manager . (a) Desert Quartzite shall be the initial Common Assets Manager subject to its right to resign as Common Assets Manager upon one hundred eighty (180) calendar days notice to the Owners. If Desert Quartzite (or any other entity) resigns as Common Assets Manager, the successor Common Assets Manager shall be selected by the Owners Committee. (b) The Common Assets Manager shall serve for a term of twenty (20) years from the first date that a Project becomes an Operating Project. No later than one hundred eighty (180) calendar days prior to the end of such term, the Owners Committee shall unanimously agree on the Common Assets Manager for the next succeeding term. If the Common Assets Manager is a third party, such party shall provide services pursuant to a contract satisfactory to the Owners Committee and consistent with (but not limited to) the requirements that would be applicable to the Common Assets Manager pursuant to this Agreement if the Common Assets Manager were one of the Owners. The foregoing shall apply with respect to each successive twenty (20) year period until this Agreement is terminated. 4.2 Powers and Duties of Common Assets Manager . The Common Assets Manager shall be authorized and shall exercise commercially reasonable efforts to do the following on behalf of each of the Owners; provided, however, that the Common Assets Manager shall not be bound by a fiduciary duty to such Owners: (a) Operate and maintain the Common Assets in accordance with Prudent Industry Practice, CAISO Protocols, Applicable Laws and the provisions in the Interconnection Agreements which specifically relate to the maintenance and management of the Common Facilities, but solely to the extent such maintenance and management terms and provisions are specifically detailed and described in a written notice delivered to the Common Assets Manager by the Owner that is party to the applicable Interconnection Agreement, and commercially reasonable terms included in any insurance policies covering the Common Assets of which the Common Assets Manager has received notice. The Common Assets Manager either directly or through one or more subcontractors will provide for the operations and maintenance of the Common Assets, including procurement of spare parts and such other services as may be desirable consistent with Prudent Industry Practice and Applicable Laws. In connection with any scheduled operation and maintenance, upon reasonable notice to the Owner(s) affected, the Common Assets Manager is authorized to require each Owner, upon no less than five (5) Business Days notice, to disconnect all or any portions of its Project, in accordance with Prudent Industry Practice, CAISO Protocols and in compliance with the terms of this Agreement. The Common Assets Manager shall coordinate with the Owner(s) affected to schedule the interruption, to the extent possible consistent with the standards set forth above, at a time least likely to adversely affect such Owners projects, and to minimize the length of the interruption. Without limiting the generality of the foregoing, the Common Assets Manager shall operate and maintain the Common Assets in a non-discriminatory manner, treating each Owner and its Project equally and fairly; (b) Subject to Section 5.7, prepare annual budgets for estimated Common Expenses, inclusive of all expected third party costs and a reasonable estimation of the Common Assets Managers salaries, wages and overhead for the following year, and budget amendments as required with respect to the Common Assets and present such budgets and budget amendments for review and approval by the Owners Committee (in the case of each annual budget, by no later than October 1 of the year prior to the year to which the budget relates); (c) Maintain books and records related to the Common Assets in accordance with United States generally acceptable accounting principles and make such books and records available to each of the Owners upon the request of such Owner during the Common Assets Managers regular business hours; (d) Procure policies of insurance covering Common Assets Managers performance under this Agreement; (e) Perform, in accordance with Prudent Industry Practice, such other duties pertaining to the Common Assets as may be specified by the Owners Committee and agreed to by the Common Assets Manager; (f) Execute such contracts and other documents as are necessary or appropriate to carry out the duties enumerated in Sections 4.2(a) through 4.2(e); (g) Submit statements to the Owners pursuant to Section 4.7(a) with respect to, and pay (to the extent of funds paid to it by the Owners pursuant to Section 4.7(a) or otherwise), bills and charges of third parties related to or in connection with the carrying out of the duties and obligations of the Common Assets Manager pursuant to this Agreement; (h) Upon the request of any Owner, promptly provide to such Owner a statement, in such detail as may be reasonably requested by such Owner, of the amounts paid or payable or reimbursed or reimbursable by such Owner pursuant to Section 4.7; (i) Notify each Owner of (i) the assertion of any claim for bodily injury or property damage in excess of Fifty Thousand Dollars ($50,000) or greater related to the Common Assets promptly following the Common Assets Managers knowledge of any such assertion and (ii) the Common Assets Managers knowledge of the occurrence of an event likely, in the reasonable determination of the Common Assets Manager, to result in the assertion of such a claim promptly following any such occurrence. If any loss, damage or impairment to the Common Assets occurs, the Common Assets Manager shall apply the proceeds of any insurance policy with respect thereto to repair, replace or restore the Common Assets to their prior condition if and to the extent permitted or required pursuant to the provisions of this Agreement; (j) Prepare, submit to each Owner for review and comment, and file in a timely manner any and all property, sales and other use and/or ad valorem tax returns required to be filed with respect to the Common Assets; and include in budgets submitted to the Owners and pay in a timely manner any property sales and other use and/or ad valorem tax owed in connection therewith, taking advantage of all available discounts for early payment (it being agreed, however, that each Owner shall have the right to protest any property sales and other use and/or ad valorem tax assessment against the Common Assets, and shall be entitled to recoup its costs in such contest to the extent they can be recouped out of tax savings achieved, whether in a single year or series of years); (k) Update Exhibit C in the event any Owner assigns all or a portion of its Common Facilities Ownership Percentage together with a corresponding portion of its Maximum Interconnection Capacity; and (l) Except as permitted by this Agreement, the Common Assets Manager shall not assign, subcontract or otherwise delegate its obligations hereunder other than to an Affiliate thereof which has sufficient skilled, knowledgeable and experienced personnel to perform the obligations of the Common Assets Manager in accordance with the requirements of this Agreement or direct and manage the performance of such functions by the counterparty to any applicable Maintenance Agreement, without the consent of the Owners Committee. Any work to be performed by the Common Assets Manager that is outside of the scope set forth in this Section 4.2 shall be addressed in a separate written agreement or an amendment to this Agreement. 4.3 Limitations on Common Assets Managers Authority . Notwithstanding Section 4.2 above, following the Effective Date the Common Assets Manager shall not be permitted to do or take any of the following actions without the express prior written consent of the Owners Committee: (a) Disposition of Assets. Selling, leasing, pledging, mortgaging, conveying, licensing, exchanging or otherwise transferring or disposing of any material property or assets comprising the Common Assets except in the ordinary course in instances where any disposed items are being repaired or replaced; (b) Contracts. Executing, amending, modifying, terminating or supplementing any Common Project Agreement, Common License and Permit or Common Real Property Document in a manner that materially and adversely affects an Owner or that does not comply with the then-applicable annual budget; (c) Borrowing. Borrowing any money on behalf of or in the name of the Owners, utilizing the Owners property as security for any loans, obligating the Owners as guarantors, endorsers, sureties or accommodation parties, or otherwise pledging the credit of the Owners in any way other than the incurring of trade accounts in the ordinary course of business (provided, however, nothing in this clause shall be deemed to prevent or prohibit any Owner from borrowing funds, issuing guarantees, or encumbering its assets, including its Proportionate Share, in connection with any corporate financing or any project financing of such Owners Project); (d) Loans. Lending any money, or extending any credit, on behalf of or in the name of the Owners; (e) Affiliate Contracts. Executing, amending, modifying, terminating or supplementing any agreements with Affiliates of the Common Assets Manager on behalf of the Owners; (f) Lawsuits and Settlements. Settling, compromising, assigning, pledging, transferring, releasing or consenting to do the same, any claim, suit, debt, demand or judgment against, or due or by the Owners or the Common Assets Manager on behalf of the Owners, submitting any such claim, dispute or controversy to arbitration or judicial process, or stipulation thereof to a judgment, or consent to do the same to the extent that any of the foregoing relate to an amount in controversy in excess of One Million and No/100 Dollars ($1,000,000) or the amount covered by applicable insurance proceeds (whichever is lower); (g) Expenditures. Making any expenditure on behalf of the Owners for any equipment, materials, assets or other items or services, or making any capital or other non-recurring expenditure, or consenting or agreeing to do any of the foregoing unless otherwise contemplated in the Common Project Agreements or contemplated in the then applicable annual budget proposed by the Common Assets Manager and approved, in writing, by the Owners, provided, however, that the Common Assets Manager may make reasonable expenditures beyond the applicable annual budget to respond to an emergency and/or to comply with Applicable Laws; or (h) Owner Directives. Taking any action with respect to the Common Assets that is contradictory to an express directive or instruction given by the Owners. 4.4 Removal of Common Assets Manager . The Common Assets Manager may be removed (a) pursuant to Section 9.6(b), or (b) for cause by any Owner; provided that each of the following conditions are satisfied: (i) the Common Assets Manager has defaulted in its material obligations under this Agreement; (ii) the Owner seeking removal of the Common Assets Manager for cause has provided written notice to the Common Assets Manager and the other Owner(s) of such default by the Common Assets Manager hereunder, which notice shall contain a general description of the facts and circumstances giving rise to such default; and (iii) the Common Assets Manager has failed to cure such default described in the notice within thirty (30) days after delivery of such written notice; provided that, if such default is not reasonably capable of being cured within thirty (30) days, then the Common Assets Manager shall have an additional period of time, but in no event more than ninety (90) days from the delivery of such written notice to cure such default. No removal of the Common Assets Manager shall be effective unless and until a successor Common Assets Manager is appointed by the Owners (such successor however may not be the person or company that has been acting as the removed Common Assets Manager); provided, however, that notwithstanding anything to the contrary contained herein, if the Common Assets Manager is removed pursuant to Section 9.6(b), then the other Owner(s) shall select the Common Assets Manager. Notwithstanding anything herein to the contrary contained herein, no removal of an Owner as the Common Assets Manager shall affect such Owners rights as an Owner, and no default by an Owner as the Common Assets Manager shall constitute a default by that Owner in its capacity as an Owner. 4.5 Step-in Rights . (a) If the Common Assets Manager defaults in its material obligations under this Agreement or fails to perform any of its material obligations under this Agreement, in each case, after the receipt of a written notice from an Owner identifying such breach or non-performance and the expiration of a thirty (30) day cure period (which cure period may be extended for up to ninety (90) days if the breach or non-performance cannot reasonably be cured within such thirty (30) day period and the Common Assets Manager is otherwise exercising commercially reasonable efforts to effectuate a cure or remedy such non-performance), then such Owner shall have the right, exercisable upon written notice to the Common Assets Manager and the other Owner(s) (Step-In Notice), to step-in and effectuate such cure or perform on behalf of the Common Assets Manager after the expiration of the relevant cure period (or to cause a third party to step-in and effectuate such cure or perform such task); provided that if more than one Owner delivers a Step-In Notice, all such Owners shall coordinate with one another in their exercise of such step-in rights. (b) Each Owner shall additionally have a license, on behalf of the Common Assets Manager and the other Owner(s), to enter onto the property covered by the Real Property Rights to: (i) inspect any facilities constructed or maintained thereon, including, but not limited to, the Common Facilities, (ii) promptly implement, supervise, monitor, organize and undertake activities necessary to deal with emergency situations affecting the Common Facilities involving risks to person or property or interfering with the normal operation of the Common Facilities or the Projects if the Common Assets Manager is unable to resolve such issues on an emergency basis such items have not been remedied by the Common Assets Manager, (iii) perform or install necessary or beneficial repairs and/or upgrades to the Common Facilities which the Common Assets Manager has failed to implement or undertake the following five (5) Business Days prior written notice from such Owner, and (iv) cure any breaches or defaults existing with respect to the Common Real Property Documents. 4.6 Authorized Expenditures . To the extent included in an annual budget or a budget amendment approved and effective pursuant to Sections 5.7 through 5.9 of this Agreement, each of the Operating Owners shall reimburse the Common Assets Manager pro rata in accordance with its Proportionate Share: (a) the salaries, wages and related indirect and reasonable overhead costs for the Common Assets Managers personnel who perform the duties and obligations of the Common Assets Manager pursuant to this Agreement, and (b) all reasonable payments made by the Common Assets Manager to third parties related to or in connection with the carrying out of the duties and obligations of the Common Assets Manager pursuant to this Agreement. The Common Assets Manager will not be entitled to recovery with respect to any costs or payments (including, pursuant to any judgment, decree, injunction, Order or decision by any Governmental Authority) incurred or owing by the Common Assets Manager as a result of or in connection with any mistake, action, inaction or omission constituting gross negligence, fraud or willful misconduct by the Common Assets Manager. 4.7 Reimbursement of Approved Costs . (a) Funds to pay for amounts expended pursuant to Section 4.6 shall be paid by each Operating Owner at the beginning of each calendar month in accordance with the then applicable annual budget. Not later than five (5) Business Days prior to the start of each calendar month (or such other billing period as is agreed by the Operating Owners), the Common Assets Manager shall deliver to each Operating Owner a statement and accounting showing the computation in reasonable detail of the amount to be advanced to the account to pay for such expenditures, which shall be within budgeted figures for the coming month adjusted for any surplus funds or funding inadequacies carried over from the latest completed month as accounted for in such statement and accounting. The Common Assets Manager shall furnish any receipts, documents, and other information in connection with each such statement as may reasonably show the basis for individual billings, charges, and cost computations, up to the date of such statement. The Common Assets Manager shall promptly provide to each Operating Owner such receipts, documents and other information in connection with each such statement as such Operating Owner may reasonably request. Within thirty (30) calendar days after receipt of each such statement, each Operating Owner shall make a report in writing to the Common Assets Manager of any dispute concerning such statement. Each Operating Owner shall pay to the Common Assets Manager any amount undisputed by such Operating Owner set forth in such statement within ten (10) Business Days. Any dispute concerning a statement shall be subject to the dispute resolution process set forth in Section 10.1. Such payment shall be made by each Operating Owner to the Common Assets Manager in immediately available funds by electronic wire transfer, or by deposit otherwise made within ten (10) Business Days after resolution of the dispute, into the account designated in writing from time to time by the Common Assets Manager for such purpose. (b) The Common Assets Manager shall make available during regular business hours, for inspection and audit by each of the Operating Owners, all books and records of the Common Assets Manager evidencing the amounts contained in each statement and accounting provided to such Operating Owner pursuant to Section 4.7(a). Such books and records shall be retained by the Common Assets Manager for such period as the Owners Committee may determine, but not less than one (1) year; and such books and records shall be made available by the Common Assets Manager for inspection and audit by each of the Operating Owners during the Common Assets Managers regular business hours. The costs and expenses of any inspection or audit requested by an Operating Owner shall be borne by the Operating Owner requesting such inspection or audit. (c) The Common Assets Manager also shall permit any Owner to inspect the books and records it maintains on behalf of the Owners during regular business hours, provided that such Owner provides at least one (1) Business Days notice of such inspection and complies with the safety requirements imposed by the Common Assets Manager on all visitors. 4.8 NERC and Regional Entity Requirements . (a) Each Owner will register with NERC or the Regional Entity as Generator Owner and Generator Operator (as defined by NERC). In the event that an Owner or a Governmental Authority determines that the Common Assets operate in a manner or perform functions which require that the Owners and/or operator register with NERC or the Regional Entity as a Transmission Owner and/or Transmission Operator, (i) the Owners shall promptly meet to determine which entity or entities shall register with NERC or the Regional Entity as the Transmission Owner and/or Transmission Operator, and (ii) all third-party costs and expenses, fees, losses, damages, liabilities, claims, judgments, liens and penalties, including, without limitation, reasonable attorneys and consultants fees, related to, associated with or in connection with fulfilling the requirements under the NERC and Regional Entity standards that are applicable to the Transmission Owner and/or Transmission Operator for the Common Assets and the Owners operation and maintenance of the Common Assets in connection therewith (TO/TOP Expenses) shall be apportioned between the Owners in accordance with its Proportionate Share. (b) Each Owner shall be solely responsible for any TO/TOP Expenses (including, without limitation, fines and/or penalties) caused by such Owners breach of this Agreement. In the event that the Common Assets are jurisdictional transmission assets which, as reasonably determined by the Owners, require the Owners to register with NERC or the Regional Entity as a Transmission Owner and/or Transmission Operator, the Owners shall not take any action in violation of any NERC or Regional Entity requirements. (c) Owners and the Common Assets Manager shall not take any action, or refrain from taking any action, to intentionally cause the Common Facilities to be subjected to the NERC or Regional Entity compliance requirements described above in Sections 4.8(a) and 4.8(b). Article 5 OWNERS COMMITTEE 5.1 Establishment of Committee; Voting . There is hereby established an Owners Committee for the Owners to take all actions which have not been expressly delegated to the Common Assets Manager pursuant to Article 4, except as otherwise provided in Section 2.6 or Section 5.8, and to take all other actions that all of the Owners may, from time to time, agree in writing that the Owners Committee is authorized to take in connection with the ownership (as applicable), construction, rebuilding, operation, maintenance, repair, replacement and removal of the Common Assets, or any portion thereof. Each Owner shall have a representative on the Owners Committee. Each Owner shall have the right to cast one vote with respect to any decision, approval or other action to be made by the Owners Committee. If an Owner is entitled to vote on the matter presented to the Owners Committee and is participating in a meeting of the Owners Committee but does not vote either in favor of or against any matter subject to a decision, approval or other action of the Owners Committee pursuant to this Agreement, such Owner shall be deemed to have voted against it. Except as provided in Sections 2.6, 5.6 and 5.7, a matter shall be deemed approved by the Owners Committee if it shall have been approved by a simple majority of all of the votes of the Owners affected by the matter before the Owners Committee, regardless of whether such Owners or their representative members on the Owners Committee are in attendance at the meeting. 5.2 Appointment of Members; Alternates . Except as provided in Section 5.6, each Owner shall have one (1) vote and have the right to appoint one (1) member to the Owners Committee, which appointment shall be deemed effective upon notice to the other Owner(s). Any Owner (or its successors and assigns, acting collectively) may change its Owners Committee member(s) by giving notice of such changes to each other Owner. Any Owner (or its successors and assigns, acting collectively), by giving notice to each other Owner, may, for purposes of any decision, approval or other action to be made by the Owners Committee pursuant to this Agreement, appoint an alternate or alternates to serve on the Owners Committee in the place of, and to cast the vote of, the regular Owners Committee member appointed by such Owner. 5.3 Meetings . The Owners Committee shall meet at such time and place as may be agreed upon by the members of the Owners Committee and the Owners Committee shall meet at such other times and places as may be requested by any Owners Committee member by notice to each other Owners Committee member at least ten (10) calendar days prior to such meeting. Members of the Owners Committee may participate in such meetings in person or by means of conference telephone calls or similar communications during which all persons participating in the meeting can hear each other. Participation in a meeting by means of conference telephone calls or similar communications shall be deemed to constitute presence in person at the meeting. No actions or decisions of the Owners Committee may be taken or made at any meeting without all of the Owners Committee members being present. 5.4 Decisions by Written Action . Any decisions, approvals and other actions that may be taken at a meeting of the Owners Committee may be taken without a meeting if all Owners Committee members consent thereto in writing. The Owners Committee may, by the unanimous vote of the members of the Owners Committee, adopt procedures for review or approval of matters or for the taking of other actions concerning the Common Assets. 5.5 Subcommittees . The Owners Committee may appoint such subcommittees as it deems necessary or appropriate and, by the unanimous vote of all of the members of the Owners Committee, may delegate approval authority to such subcommittees with respect to matters concerning the Common Assets. Members of a subcommittee are not required to otherwise be a member of the Owners Committee. 5.6 Operation-Only Decisions . Notwithstanding anything in this Agreement to the contrary, the following shall require the unanimous approval of the Operating Owners on the Owners Committee: (a) approval or amendment of the annual budgets and budget amendments prepared by the Common Assets Manager pursuant to Section 4.2(b); (b) approval of contracts or commitments involving or expected to involve aggregate expenditures of more than $50,000.00 for expenses within a budget approved by the Owners Committee (or otherwise in effect pursuant to Section 5.7); (c) approval of the incurrence of costs, with respect to any line item in a budget approved by the Owners Committee (or otherwise in effect pursuant to Section 5.7) in excess of such line item budget; (d) approval of the incurrence of aggregate costs for any calendar year in excess of the total budgeted costs for such year as set forth in a budget approved by the Owners Committee (or otherwise in effect pursuant to Section 5.7); (e) any decision to remove from service permanently or otherwise to sell, transfer, assign or dispose of all or any part of the Common Facilities; and (f) any decision to incur or to authorize the Common Assets Manager to incur any indebtedness related to the Common Facilities that the Owners would be obligated to repay pursuant to this Agreement, other than a Lenders Lien against an individual Owners Proportionate Share incurred in accordance with Section 8.1(b). 5.7 Decisions Requiring Unanimous Approval of all Owners . The unanimous approval of all Owners on the Owners Committee shall be required for decisions that both (a) increase the amount of Common Expenses to be incurred or paid and (b) are reasonably expected to negatively affect in a material and disproportionate way the interests of the non-Operating Owners in the Common Assets vis a vis the interests of the Operating Owners in the Common Assets. 5.8 Budgets . If for any reason the Owners Committee does not approve an annual budget prior to the end of the eleventh (11th) month of the preceding calendar year (other than the budget applicable during the first year), the budget for such preceding year shall apply to the current year, subject to an increase or decrease in such budget to reflect the change in the GDPIPD for all goods and services during the twelve (12)-month period ending with the tenth (10th) month of such preceding year. 5.9 Emergency Actions . The Common Assets Manager (or any Owner, if Common Assets Manager is unavailable or fails to act) shall have the right but not the duty to proceed with an item that has not been approved (even if it has been disapproved) as provided in this Article 5, if the Common Assets Manager (or any Owner, if Common Assets Manager is unavailable or fails to act) determines in its reasonable judgment that such action is required to avoid an imminent threat of loss of life or property or is required to avoid an imminent threat of interruption of service to the Owner of a Project; provided, however, that Common Assets Manager (or any Owner, if Common Assets Manager is unavailable or fails to act) must give notice of such action to each Owner as soon as reasonably possible and further provided that if the Common Assets Manager (or any Owner) takes such action on a disapproved item and if the determination made in any subsequent review of the decision is that the item was not consistent with Prudent Industry Practice, then the Common Assets Manager (or such Owner) shall not be entitled to reimbursement for any of the cost or expense of such action. 5.10 Tax Election . Each of the Owners shall, to the extent permitted by Section 761 of the Code, elect as provided in Treasury Regulation Section 1.761-2 to exclude from the provisions of Subchapter K of the Code any organization that they may otherwise comprise by virtue of this Agreement. 5.11 Deadlocks . If the Owners Committee reaches deadlock on an issue, such that the Owners fall short of unanimity (a Deadlock), and any Party gives written notice to the other(s) that such has occurred, then the Owners will use all reasonable efforts to reach a satisfactory solution by referring the Deadlock to senior management of each of the Owners or their parent entities. In the event that a Deadlock has been declared, senior management of the Owners or their parent entities will meet as soon as possible, on no less than five (5) Business Days notice, unless specifically agreed otherwise. Any Deadlock that cannot be resolved by further negotiations by such senior management shall be determined as set forth in Article 10. Article 6 COVENANTS 6.1 Covenants of the Owners . The Owners hereby covenant as follows: (a) Mechanics Liens. Each Owner shall not permit any mechanics liens arising out of its activities to exist against the Common Assets. If an Owner wishes to contest any such lien, that Owner shall, within sixty (60) calendar days after it receives notice of the lien, provide a bond or other security to the other Owner(s) as those other Owner(s) may reasonably request, or remove such lien from the affected property pursuant to Applicable Law. (b) Environmental Laws. Each Owner shall comply with Environmental Laws in connection with its separate activities of its Project and Common Assets. Each Owner agrees to indemnify the other Owner(s) and the Common Assets Manager against such Owners violation of the Environmental Laws on its Project and Common Assets, including such violations by its agents or contractors. The foregoing indemnities shall not apply to the extent of any gross negligence or willful misconduct by the Party being indemnified, or to any acts or omissions of the Common Assets Manager conducted with respect to the Common Assets in accordance with this Agreement and approved by the Owners Committee. (c) Taxes. Subject to Section 4.2(j), each Owner shall pay, when due, all real and personal property taxes and assessments, general or special, levied against its separately owned Project facilities and/or tis Project operations subject to such Partys right to contest by appropriate legal proceedings the validity or applicability of any such taxes and assessments; provided that no such contest shall be permitted if it would expose the Common Assets to a risk of loss by forfeiture or otherwise. (d) Compliance with Law. Each Owner shall, at its sole cost and expense, promptly comply with all Applicable Laws and Common Licenses and Permits and with all covenants, conditions and restrictions in effect regulating the use of the Common Assets or any facilities owned by such Owner thereon until this Agreement is terminated; provided however, that such Owner shall have the right to contest by appropriate legal proceedings and in its own name the validity or applicability of any such Applicable Law; provided that no such contest shall be permitted if it would expose the Common Assets to a risk of loss by forfeiture or otherwise. (e) Conduct of Activities. Each Owner shall (i) conduct its operations and activities of its Project and the Common Assets in accordance with all Applicable Laws and Prudent Industry Practices, and (ii) to the extent necessary to avoid a material adverse effect with respect to the condition or operation of the Common Assets or an increase in insurance premiums with respect thereto, keep its facilities in good condition and repair, in good and efficient working order and in a safe condition. Neither any Owner nor the Common Assets Manager shall conduct its operations or activities, or use or permit the use of the Common Assets or any part thereof or its facilities in any manner that will cause physical damage to the Common Assets or any part thereof, or cause an increase in insurance premiums with respect thereto and each Owner (and the Common Assets Manager, if not an Owner) shall be responsible for any such physical damage (but shall not incur any liability for any down-time resulting from any operations or activities conducted in accordance with Applicable Laws, Prudent Industry Practices and otherwise in accordance with this Agreement). Each Owner shall exercise reasonable efforts to coordinate with the other Owner(s) in the timing and duration of maintenance to the transmission lines on the Common Assets and the other portions of the Owners Projects (to the extent maintenance of such Projects would materially impair the use by the other Owner(s) of the Common Assets or the transmission lines on such Common Assets); provided however, that if the Owners cannot agree to the timing and duration of any such maintenance, any dispute shall be subject to the dispute resolution process set forth in Section 10.1; provided further, however, that each Owner shall have the right to perform any maintenance required in the case of any action which it determines in its reasonable judgment is required to avoid an imminent threat of loss of life or property or is required to avoid an imminent threat of interruption of service to the Owner in accordance with the process set forth in Section 5.8. (f) Confidentiality of Owner Information. Each Owner agrees to maintain the confidentiality of the Information, except that Information may be disclosed (a) to its Affiliates, managers, partners, directors, officers, employees, advisors, agents, consultants, lenders, and potential lenders, investors and purchasers to or of an Owner or any of its Affiliates (and their respective advisors, consultants and counsel); it being understood that the Persons to whom such disclosure is made will be informed of the confidential nature of such Information and, other than with respect to a ratings agency, required to keep such Information confidential pursuant to a confidentiality agreement similar in nature to this Section 6.1(f) or be under a duty to keep such Information confidential that is at least as restrictive as the confidentiality obligations set forth in this Section 6.1(f), (b) to the extent requested by any regulatory authority having jurisdiction over the Owners, (c) to the extent required by Applicable Laws or regulations or by any subpoena or similar legal process, (d) in any legal action or proceeding relating to this Agreement or the Common Assets, or (e) to the extent such Information (i) becomes publicly available other than as a result of a breach of this Section or (ii) becomes available to any Owner on a non-confidential basis from a source other than the Owner to whom such Information relates. For purposes of this Agreement, Information means all information received pursuant to this Agreement or during the design, use or operation of the Common Assets from an Owner or relating to an Owner or any of the Projects or businesses, other than any such information that is available to any Owner on a non-confidential basis prior to disclosure by the Owner to whom such Information relates. Article 7 INSURANCE 7.1 Insurance for Common Assets . Each Operating Owner shall, at its expense, maintain a commercial general liability insurance policy insuring it and the other Owner(s) (including any Owner that does not have a Project that has reached completion of commissioning) against loss or liability caused by such Owners use of the Common Assets and the land on which they are located, in an amount not less than Ten Million Dollars ($10,000,000) of combined single limit liability coverage per occurrence, accident or incident, which has a commercially reasonable deductible. Each Owner shall, at its expense, maintain a policy of casualty insurance covering the Common Assets in an amount equal to the full replacement cost thereof. Certificates of such insurance evidencing the coverages required by this Agreement shall be provided to the other Owners upon reasonable request. Each Owner shall have the right to use a qualified program of self-insurance to meet the insurance requirements and may also provide any such insurance pursuant to one or more blanket insurance policies maintained by such Party or its Affiliates. Each Owner shall include an endorsement to liability policy naming the other Owner(s), and their successors, assigns, affiliates, partners, directors, officers, employees, representatives, and agents as additional insureds, (except statutory workers compensation insurance). The commercial General Liability additional insured endorsement shall be ISO FORM CG21 10 or its equivalent). Liability policies shall include a waiver of any right of subrogation in favor of each Owner, their parents, division, Affiliates, subsidiaries, co-lessees, co-venturers, agents, directors, officers, employees, servants, representatives, subcontractors and insurers of any right of the insurers to any set-off or counterclaim or any other deduction, whether by attachment or otherwise, and respect of any liability of any such Person insured under such policy (and the Commercial General Liability Policy waiver of subrogation endorsement shall be ISO Form CG 24 04 or its equivalent). Article 8 TRANSFER OF INTERESTS; LIENS 8.1 Restrictions on Transfer . No Owner shall assign, sell, dispose of, give or otherwise transfer, directly or indirectly, (collectively assign or assignment) all or any portion of its undivided interest in the Common Assets or its rights under this Agreement to any person, except with the consent of the other Owner(s). The consent requirements of this Section 8.1 shall not be required for a sale, assignment or transfer by an Owner (a Transferring Party) in the following circumstances, and for the avoidance of doubt, any sale, assignment or transfer in the following circumstances may be effectuated without the consent of the other Owners, but the Transferring Party shall provide the other Owners and the Common Assets Manager with notice of any such sale, assignment or transfer promptly following the effectuation thereof: (a) the assignee or transferee is an entity with which the Transferring Party has consolidated or into which the Transferring Party has merged or which acquires by conveyance, transfer or lease all or substantially all of the assets of such Transferring Party and such purchaser, assignee, lessee or assignee shall have agreed in writing to assume all of the future obligations of such Transferring Party under this Agreement; (b) the assignee or transferee owns (or will own upon the assignment or transfer) an appropriate equivalent ownership interest in the Project(s) or any portion thereof owned by the Transferring Party which produces electricity transmitted over the lines supported by the Common Assets; or (c) when EDF RD is transferring some or all of its Common Facilities Ownership Percentage in the Common Assets together with a proportional share of its Maximum Interconnection Capacity and its rights and obligations under this Agreement to a new Owner or Owner(s). The restrictions on transfer contained in this Section 8.1 shall not apply with respect to transfers of equity ownership in an Owner itself, or in connection with the transfer of assets, or equity interests in any entity, in either case owned by an Owner, member, shareholder, or other Person owning an equity interest (directly or indirectly) in an Owner. 8.2 Lenders Liens . Notwithstanding anything in this Agreement to the contrary, the Common Assets Manager and each Owner specifically agree that any Owner may at any time pledge, collaterally assign, encumber, or grant a security interest in the entirety of its own undivided Common Facilities Ownership Percentage tenancy in common interest in the Common Assets and in its rights under this Agreement to any Lender (a Lenders Lien). 8.3 Surrender and Assignment of Proportionate Share . Notwithstanding Section 8.1, any Owner may elect, but only with the consent of the Owner or Owners accepting the Common Facilities Ownership Percentage, to convey its Common Facilities Ownership Percentage and assign its rights hereunder to another Owner or Owners and, thereupon, to cease to have any right, title or interest in the Common Assets, in any Maximum Interconnection Capacity or its Common Facilities Ownership Percentage; provided that: (A) the surrendering Owner executes and delivers all instruments of transfer as may be necessary or appropriate to effect (and that do effect) the conveyance of its Common Facilities Ownership Percentage and assignment of its rights hereunder (including any rights pertaining to use the Common Facilities pertaining to its Maximum Interconnection Capacity) to, and which are reasonably satisfactory to, the remaining Owner or Owners, (B) such assignment and conveyance is accompanied by an assignment by the surrendering Owner to the remaining Owner or Owners of all its rights under this Agreement and (C) an encumbered Common Facilities Ownership Percentage may only be surrendered with the written consent of each Lender that holds a security interest in such Common Facilities Ownership Percentage and a release of such Lenders security interest therein. No surrender of an Owners Common Facilities Ownership Percentage shall relieve the surrendering Owner of any of its obligations under any agreement (including this Agreement and the obligation to pay its share of the Common Expenses through the effective date of such surrender), unless expressly provided for in this Agreement, or agreed in a writing among the Owners. 8.4 Transfer Requirements . (a) Any sale, assignment or transfer made in accordance with Section 8.1 or Section 8.2 (i) shall relieve an Owner of any past obligation under this Agreement only to the extent consented to in writing by the other Owner(s), and (ii) shall relieve an Owner of any future obligation under this Agreement, only to the extent assumed by the transferee in writing. Except as permitted in Section 8.1, no Owner may transfer all or part of its rights to use the Common Assets separately from its ownership interest in the Common Assets. Any attempted or purported sale, assignment or other transfer of any interest in the Common Assets or this Agreement made other than in accordance with this Article 8 either voluntarily or by operation of law shall be void and of no force or effect. (b) Notwithstanding anything to the contrary, no transfer of any Owners Common Facilities Ownership Percentage or interests in this Agreement shall be effective unless and until the applicable Owner has obtained any necessary approvals from FERC and any federal, state, or local regulatory agency having jurisdiction over the Common Assets (but only to the extent such consent or approval is actually required by any such agency). (c) Each Owner hereby agrees to execute and deliver such instruments of conveyance, in recordable form as applicable, as the Common Assets Manager deems necessary to vest ownership of such assignees or transferees Common Facilities Ownership Percentage of the Common Assets. 8.5 Obligations Regarding Liens . Except as provided in Section 8.2, (a) no Owner shall, directly or indirectly, create, incur or cause to exist any lien on or encumbrance (including a Permitted Lien) to be levied against or attached to the Common Facilities Ownership Percentage of any other Owner and (b) no Owner shall create, incur or permit to exist any lien or encumbrance (other than Permitted Liens) on its Common Facilities Ownership Percentage. If any such lien or encumbrance attaches or an Owner receives notice of any such lien or encumbrance, the Owner whose actual or alleged act or omission resulted in such lien or encumbrance shall cause such lien or encumbrance to be released and removed of record within fifteen (15) days of such attachment or notice, unless in the cause of clause (b) above, (y) such Owner (i) in good faith contests or disputes the validity of such liens or encumbrances, (ii) promptly commences legal action to remove such lien or encumbrance and (iii) furnishes to the other Owner(s) a bond or other acceptable security in an amount sufficient to discharge all such contested liens and encumbrances and (z) during such period the lienholders proceedings are stayed. If an Owner creates, causes or permits to exist a Permitted Lien on its Common Facilities Ownership Percentage and there is a reasonable likelihood that such Permitted Lien will interfere with any other Owners Common Facilities Ownership Percentage in any material respect, then such Owner shall promptly remove such Permitted Lien upon such Owners receipt of a written request therefor. Notwithstanding the foregoing, in accordance with Article 8, an Owner may grant a lien on or security interest in its Common Facilities Ownership Percentage with respect to such Owners Project and any Owner may obtain a judgment lien against any other Owner based on any such other Owners breach under this Agreement, or otherwise permitted at law or in equity, and not specifically prevented by this Agreement. 8.6 Succession as Owner . Any permitted purchaser, assignee or transferee (other than an assignee of a security interest pursuant to Section 8.1 prior to foreclosure thereon) shall be considered an Owner and a Party for purposes of this Agreement and the Common Assets Manager shall circulate an amended Exhibit C to the then current Owners reflecting any changes to each Owners Common Facilities Ownership Percentage resulting from any such permitted purchase, assignment or transfer promptly after receiving notice of any such changes. 8.7 Lender Protection Parties Obligations . (a) As a precondition to exercising any remedies related to any alleged default by a Party under this Agreement, any other Party shall give notice of the default to each Lender of the defaulting Party of which the non-defaulting Party has received written notice and such Lenders notice address at the same time it delivers notice of the default to the defaulting Party, specifying in detail the alleged default and the required remedy. Each such Lender shall have the same amount of time to cure the default as is given to the defaulting Party and the same right to cure any default as the defaulting Party. The cure period for each such Lender shall begin to run at the end of the cure period given to Parties in this Agreement, but in no case shall the cure period for any such Lender be less than thirty (30) calendar days after receipt of the notice of default. Any such Lender shall have the absolute right to substitute itself for the defaulting Party and perform the duties of the defaulting Party hereunder for purposes of curing such default. Each Party expressly consents to such substitution, agrees to accept such performance and authorizes any such Lender (or its employees, agents, representatives or contractors) to enter upon the Common Assets to complete such performance with all of the rights and privileges of the defaulting Party hereunder. (b) Lender Obligations. Any Lender that does not directly hold an interest under this Agreement, or whose interest is held solely for security purposes, shall have no obligation or liability to any other Party for performance of a Partys obligations under this Agreement prior to the time the Lender directly holds an interest in this Agreement, or succeeds to absolute title to a Partys interest. A Lender shall be liable to perform obligations of a Party to the other Parties under this Agreement only for and during the period it directly holds such interest. Except as otherwise provided in Section 8.3, any assignment permitted under this Agreement shall release a Party or other assignor from obligations accruing after the date that liability is assumed by a transferee, but the assigning Party shall continue to be liable to the other Parties for all performance due by the assigning Party for matters that have accrued and are unsatisfied as of the date of the assignment. Moreover, any Lender or other Person who acquires an interest in the Common Assets pursuant to foreclosure or an assignment in lieu of foreclosure shall not be liable to perform any obligations under the Agreement to the extent the same are incurred or accrue after such Lender or other Person no longer has ownership of such interest. (c) Lenders Right to Possession, Right to Acquire and Right to Assign. A Lender shall have the absolute right: (i) to assign its Lenders Lien; (ii) to exercise its rights under its Security Documents with the pledging Owner, including foreclosing, receiving, transferring, conveying or assigning the undivided interest of the Owner, in each case without obtaining the consent of the other Owner(s) or the Common Assets Manager, provided that no such assignment or a foreclosure on such assignment shall subordinate or otherwise adversely affect the rights of the other Owner(s) in and to this Agreement or the Common Assets covered hereby or the terms and provisions of Section 8.7(b); and (iii) to perform all obligations to be performed by a Party under this Agreement, or to cause a receiver to be appointed to do so. No Partys consent shall be required for any of the foregoing, and upon acquisition of an interest in the Common Assets by a Lender or any other third party who acquires the same from or on behalf of the Lender, each other Party shall recognize the Lender or such other party (as the case may be) as the pledging Partys proper successor, and this Agreement shall remain in full force and effect. (d) Opportunity to Cure. Following acquisition of an interest in the Common Assets by the Lender as a result of either foreclosure or acceptance of an assignment in lieu of foreclosure, or by a purchaser at a foreclosure sale, this Agreement shall continue in full force and effect and the Lender or party acquiring title to such interest in the Common Assets shall, as promptly as reasonably possible, commence the cure of all defaults under this Agreement and thereafter diligently process such cure to completion; provided, however, that the Lender or party acquiring title to such interest in the Common Assets shall not be required to cure those defaults which are not reasonably susceptible of being cured or performed by such party. If a Lender is prohibited by any process or injunction issued by any court or by reason of any action of any court having jurisdiction over any bankruptcy or insolvency proceeding involving the defaulting Party from commencing or prosecuting the appropriate judicial or non-judicial proceedings, then any cure period for commencing such proceedings shall be extended for the period of such prohibition. (e) Termination. Neither the bankruptcy nor the insolvency of a Party shall be grounds for terminating this Agreement as long as all payments and all other monetary charges payable by the Party under this Agreement are paid by the Lender in accordance with the terms of this Agreement. (f) New Agreement. In the event that this Agreement is rejected or disaffirmed pursuant to bankruptcy law or any other law affecting creditors rights, then, so long as a Lender has cured any such monetary default and is making commercially reasonable efforts to cure any such non-monetary default as provided herein, the non-defaulting Party(ies) shall, immediately upon request from such Lender received within ninety (90) calendar days after any such event, without demanding additional consideration therefore, enter into a common use agreement with such Lender, which new common use agreement shall (i) contain the same covenants, agreements, terms, provisions and limitations as this Agreement (except for any requirements that have been fulfilled by the Parties prior to such termination, foreclosure, rejection or disaffirmance), and (ii) be for a term commencing on the date of such termination, foreclosure, rejection or disaffirmance and continuing for the remaining term of this Agreement before giving effect to such termination, foreclosure, rejection or disaffirmance. At the option of the Lender, the new common use agreement may be executed by a designee of such Lender, with the Lender assuming the burdens and obligations of the defaulting Party thereunder. If more than one Lender makes a request for a new common use agreement pursuant hereto, then the same shall be delivered to the Lender whose lien is senior in priority. (g) Lender Consent. Notwithstanding any provision of this Agreement to the contrary, (i) a Party shall not agree to a modification or amendment of this Agreement if the same could reasonably be expected to materially reduce the rights or remedies of a Lender or impair or reduce the security for a Lenders Lien, and (ii) a Party shall not accept a termination of this Agreement without the prior consent of each Lender. (h) Further Assurances. The Owners, the Common Assets Manager and the Owners Committee shall exercise commercially reasonable efforts, at the requesting Owners cost and expense, to (i) cooperate in amending this Agreement from time to time to include any reasonable provision that may be reasonably requested by a Party or any Lender to implement the provisions contained in this Agreement or to preserve a Lenders Lien, (ii) execute any documents which may reasonably be required by a Party or a Lender to give effect to a provision of this Agreement and (iii) reasonably cooperate with the interconnection of any Project, including as necessary temporarily curtailing or discontinuing deliveries of energy from any Project for such reasonably minimal period of time as is necessary to perform the physical interconnection of a Project to the Common Assets. Article 9 DEFAULT AND REMEDIES 9.1 Demand for Payment or Performance . Upon failure of an Owner to make or cause to be made any payment when due and owing, or to perform or cause to be performed any other obligation to be performed by it, pursuant to the terms, covenants and conditions contained in this Agreement, the other Owner(s) or the Common Assets Manager may make demand upon said Owner for such payment or performance. 9.2 Payment Defaults . If an Owner fails to make or cause to be made a payment when due and owing pursuant to the terms, covenants and conditions contained in this Agreement, and such failure is not cured by such Owner within ten (10) Business Days following the date on which an Owner or the Common Assets Manager makes a demand for payment with respect to such failure pursuant to Section 9.1, such failure shall, upon the expiration of such ten (10) Business Day period, constitute a default by such Owner for purposes of this Agreement. 9.3 Performance Defaults . If an Owner materially fails to perform or cause to be performed any material obligation (other than a payment obligation) to be performed by it pursuant to the terms, covenants and conditions contained in this Agreement, and such failure is not cured by such Owner within thirty (30) Business Days following the date on which the Common Assets Manager or an Owner makes a demand for performance with respect to such failure pursuant to Section 9.1, or, if it is not reasonably practicable to cure such failure within said thirty (30) Business Day period, then within a reasonable period following the date on which such Owner receives such demand provided cure is commenced within such thirty (30) Business Day period and diligently and continuously prosecuted to completion, such failure shall, upon the expiration of the applicable grace period pursuant to this Section 9.3, constitute a default by such Owner for purposes of this Agreement. 9.4 Disputed Defaults . If an Owner disputes a default asserted against it by demand pursuant to Section 9.1, then such Owner may make or cause to be made payment of any sums in dispute or perform the obligation in dispute under protest and without prejudice to any rights or remedies that such Owner may have pursuant to any of this Agreement or at law or in equity. The Owner purportedly in default shall (i) deliver such protest in writing to the Common Assets Manager or the Owner asserting the default with respect thereto, (ii) specify in such protest the reasons upon which the protest is based and (iii) deliver a copy of such protest by first class mail to the Common Assets Manager and any Owner asserting the default. If such dispute is resolved in favor of the Owner upon whom demand was made, the Common Assets Manager or Owner making demand upon such Owner shall, by means of appropriate adjustment of amounts payable by the Owners, reimburse to such Owner the amount of any payments made under rightful protest and the amount of the costs and expenses incurred by such Owner in performing any obligation under rightful protest, each such reimbursement to be made, together with ten percent interest per annum, such interest to accrue from (and including) the date such payments were made or performance accomplished under rightful protest to (but excluding) the date of such reimbursement. 9.5 Interest on Late Payments . Any payment not made by a defaulting Owner when due and owing pursuant to the terms, covenants and conditions contained in this Agreement may be advanced by any other Owner(s) and, if so advanced, the amount of such payments shall be repayable to such other Owner(s) by the defaulting Owner with interest at the Late Payment Rate to accrue from (and including) the date such advance is made to (but excluding) the date of repayment of such advance by the defaulting Owner. 9.6 Remedies . (a) In addition to all other remedies permitted by law or under this Agreement (all of which shall be cumulative), following a default by an Owner (after notice and the expiration of any applicable cure period), the non-defaulting Owner and its Lenders or other interest holders shall be entitled to pay any amounts due by the defaulting Owner, including, but not limited to, the defaulting Owners portion of the Common Expenses, and/or perform the obligations of the defaulting Owner, and the defaulting Owner shall reimburse the performing Owners for any and all amounts paid and/or costs and expenses incurred in paying such amounts and/or rendering such performance, plus interest at the Late Payment Rate. (b) If after the Effective Date (i) an insolvency proceeding has been commenced against an Owner and such proceeding continues undismissed for sixty (60) days or (ii) an Owner institutes an insolvency proceeding with respect to itself, or admits in writing its inability to pay its indebtedness generally as it becomes due or fails generally to pay its indebtedness as it becomes due, or any action is taken by an Owner for the purpose of effecting any of the foregoing or any analogous proceeding (collectively, Insolvency Proceedings), then if that Owner is the Common Assets Manager, such Owner shall automatically be removed as the Common Assets Manager as soon as the other Owner(s) designates and appoints a replacement Common Assets Manager. As soon as the Insolvency Proceedings are completed, a successor Common Assets Manager shall be selected by the Owners Committee. (c) Notwithstanding anything to the contrary contained herein, the Owners each acknowledge and agree that it would be prejudicial to the interests of the Owners under this Agreement if any Owner were to seek partition or any other type of division of the Common Assets or file an action for such partition or division. Therefore, in consideration of such fact and for other good and valuable consideration, each of the Owners hereby waives and relinquishes any and all rights that it may have at any time or under any circumstance, including, without limitation, after a default by an Owner hereunder, to seek a partition or any other type of division of the Common Assets. 9.7 Equitable Relief . The Owners agree that damages may be an inadequate remedy for a breach by the Common Assets Manager or any Owner of its respective obligations under this Agreement, and that each Owner shall be entitled, in addition to all other remedies at law or under contract, to seek injunctive and other equitable relief, including specific performance, against any other Owner or the Common Assets Manager to prevent or eliminate any such default. 9.8 Existing Liens Not Affected . No remedy or action taken pursuant to this Article 9 by a non-defaulting Owner in connection with a default by another Owner is intended to give rise to the creation of any lien, claim or encumbrance of any non-defaulting Owner that is prior to the lien, claim or encumbrance of any Lender under any mortgage, loan, credit agreement or other security agreement or instrument of indebtedness between such Lender and such defaulting Owner existing as of the occurrence of such default by such defaulting Owner, except to the extent permitted under such mortgage, loan, credit agreement, other security agreement or instrument of indebtedness. 9.9 Separate Defaults . Each act or omission to act that constitutes a default under this Agreement shall be treated as a separate default under this Article 9. 9.10 Real Property Rights Default . To the extent an Owner is a grantee under the Real Property Rights, including as the holder of an undivided ownership interest, as a tenant-in-common therein, a default by an Owner and remedies by a non-defaulting Owner under the Real Property Rights shall be governed by the provisions of the respective Real Property Rights.
